data.description: What does it mean to survive—intellectually, politically, ecologically, or aesthetically—in a moment defined by crisis? When uncertainty and chaos prevail, those who endure must bend, not break. They must adapt, redirect, stay fluid. How do figures of water help us think survival not as a static state but as a process: precarious, contingent, always at risk of being swept under? Survival and water: two conceptual forces that converge in literary, philosophical, and political discourses across the German tradition. Whether in the form of biblical floods, rising oceans, or mythic rivers—water stages a sight of duality: It is where life and death, healing and destruction, calmness and acceleration are able to meet in a resistant stream of becoming. To survive—especially “with one’s head above water”—is to inhabit the threshold between endurance and submersion, grasping for breath, clarity, meaning. At the same time, survival carries its own paradoxes: Who survives and at what cost? What kinds of knowledge or expression survive catastrophe, exile, war, or erasure—and which are drowned out? Water leaks across genres and disciplines: as metaphor for time and memory, as site of passage and peril, as resource and threat, as a medium of cleansing, forgetting, or border-policing. Meanwhile, survival speaks equally to historical trauma and everyday precarity, to climate catastrophe and cultural memory, to the bodies that wash ashore and those that remain submerged in the archive. This conference seeks contributions that take up the dual themes of survival and water—literally, figuratively, or formally—as critical frameworks. We welcome engagements with water as metaphor, medium, matter, and menace, and with survival as a philosophical problem, a narrative form, or a historical condition. What does it mean to be in over one’s head—psychically, politically, or ecologically? How might “keeping one’s head above water” register both resistance and exhaustion? How are the concepts of water and survival marshaled by thinkers, writers, artists, or regimes? How do literature, film, and theory reckon with flood, immersion, drowning, or breath? What kinds of bodies are asked to stay afloat, and at what cost? Brief: how do we keep our head above water; how do we survive the current?
data.name: HEAD ABOVE WATER: Surviving the Current. Rutgers German Graduate Student Conference

data.description: Dear Graduate Students and Faculty in Life Science and Biomedical Programs,   Abstract submission is open for graduate students to present at the 2026 Annual Graduate Student Research Symposium, sponsored by the Molecular Biosciences Graduate Student Organization (MBGSO) and Rutgers School of Graduate Studies.    Date: Friday, March 6th, 2026 Time: 9:30 am - 4:30 pm  Location: Life Science Building Atrium, Busch Campus Keynote Speaker: Joseph Contessa, MD, PhD, Chair of Radiation Oncology, Head of Translational Research, Rutgers Cancer Center    Please use this link or the QR code in the flyer attached to register to attend and/or submit an abstract.  Note that abstract submission deadline is January 30th, 2026.    We are looking for faculty to judge the posters and talks. data.description: All BME-affiliated undergraduates, graduate students, and postdocs are invited to present their research through either posters or oral presentations. The symposium is open to the entire BME department, including non-BME students conducting research in BME labs. A panel of judges will assess both posters and presentations, and winners will receive a prize! Faculty interested in participating as judges, please reach out to us at rutgersbess@gmail.com to let us know! Please use this Google form to indicate your interest in presenting: https://forms.gle/9mdozEzRJ2NRjXgP8.   To submit an abstract, we will ask for the following: 1. Title, Authors, and Affiliations.2. An abstract (cannot exceed 250 words) that can include the following sections:   - Introduction   - Materials and Methods   - Results (If Applicable)   - Conclusions   Abstracts are due on 03/01/26 at 11:59 pm. All participants are welcome to present their posters, and those chosen for an oral presentation will be notified by the week of 03/08/26.  We hope you will join us to showcase our community's outstanding research, celebrate your achievements, and foster new collaborations and discussions! We will send out further details about the event schedule and logistics at a later date.

data.description: As a graduate student, teaching assistant, instructor, or friend, you may wonder about academic accommodations and accessibility. The Office of Disability Services is hosting a drop-in afternoon for graduate students interested in learning about the services that ODS provides. Come stop by the Graduate Student Lounge or join via Zoom and meet Coordinator Nychey Michel to discuss accommodations for: hearing, vision, and mobility conditions, learning disabilities, psychological diagnoses (such as anxiety or depression), chronic illnesses, traumatic brain injuries, ADHD, Autism Spectrum Disorder, and more. Bring yourself or bring a friend to ask questions and learn about outreach efforts. Coffee and donuts will be provided while supplies last!   Questions or accommodation requests specific to this event? Please email dsoffice@echo.rutgers.edu, call 848-202-3111, or visit ODS in Lucy Stone Hall, Suite A145, Livingston Campus.

data.description: Come join us on Sunday, April 19, for Haru's biggest event of the semester, Spring 2026 Showcase! Our goal is to share Korean pop culture through the art of dance. This event is open to everyone: general members, families, Rutgers students, and non-Rutgers students! Our showcase is our biggest event, where our members get to showcase a multitude of K-pop performances they’ve been preparing for months for our audience. There are two acts with an intermission, which includes a raffle with a bunch of prizes our audience can partake in and possibly win big! And the best part is that admission is FREE for all!  You don't have to be performing to attend, so come out and support our performers! ♡ Let's cheer each other on and enjoy each other's company! You may also get some sweet treats, snacks, and refreshments from us to enjoy while watching performances 👀 Our showcase is also livestreamed on our YouTube page for audience members who cannot attend in person, but would love to support our performers! If you're watching from online, thank you for supporting Haru Dance ♡ More information on parking will be detailed here later in the semester. Contact us directly on IG: @harudance_official or Email: haru.kdcc@gmail.com if you have any questions! Can't wait to see y'all soon!
